==English==
=== Transitive Verb ===
# To [[brood]], [[raise]], or [[maintain]] eggs, organisms, or living tissue through the provision of ideal environmental conditions.
#:'''1975:''' Part of our problem in praying for our children, he suggested, is the time lage, the necessary slow maturation of our prayers.  But that's the way of God's rhythm in nature.  For instance, the hend must patiently sit on her eggs to '''incubate''' them before the baby chicks hatch. - [[w:Catherine Marshall|Catherine Marshall]],  ''Adventures in Prayer'': page 46.  New York: Ballantine Books, December 1976
#:'''1985:''' The mother dead these fourteen years did '''incubate''' in her own bosom the creature who would carry her off. - [[w:Cormac McCarthy|Cormac McCarthy]], ''Blood Meridian'': page 3.  New York: Vintage International, May 1992
#:'''2004:''' The female cichlid fish are called "mouth breeders," which means they '''incubate''' eggs in their mouth. - [[w:A. J. Jacobs|A. J. Jacobs]], ''The Know-It-All : One Man's Humble Quest to Become the Smartest Person in the World'': page 50.  New York: Simon & Schuster, 2004
# To incubate metaphorically; to [[ponder]] an idea slowly and deliberately as if in preperation for [[hatching]] it.
#:'''1992:''' When you've got your theme&ndash;let the concept incubate. Walk around with it, sleep on it. - [[w:Sheila Davis|Sheila Davis]],  ''The Songwriters Idea Book: 40 Strategies to Excite Your Imagination, Help You Design Distinctive Songs, and Keep Your Creative Flow'': page 96.  Cincinnati: Writer's Digest Books, 1992

